i></ul><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 13.35pt; padding-left:0.85pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Two profiles use the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">$1 </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a day measure</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. The World Bank moved to the $1.25 a day threshold in 2008. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Somalia </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">figure of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">43% in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">$1 a d</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ay poverty in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">2002 </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">is not sourced, and is not provided by the World Bank. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Zambia profile </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">uses both $1.25 and $1 for rural poverty. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">It </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">also notes </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">14 years of growth</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in Zambia </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">has not benefitted most poor people</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">: </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">poverty levels </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">actually </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">increased</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">from 62.1% in 1996 to 74.5% today</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 13.35pt; padding-left:0.85pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Some </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">profiles use national poverty lines</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> (NPLs)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, but </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">do not </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">explain </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">level</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> these are </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">set</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">at nor </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">how they relate to $1.25 a day</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> An </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">exception is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Mozambique which states that 54.7% live below </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">an NPL set at </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">$0.68.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Using national definitions: </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">“over one third”</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">of people in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Afghanistan </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">are in poverty; poverty has gone from </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">39% to 30% over five years </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Ethiopia</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Kyrgyzstan </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">has </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">32% below </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a national line; 26% of people are below an </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">NPL </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">(presumably </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">given </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">no </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">$1.25 data</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Rwanda </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">has </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">45% poor and 24% extreme poor based on </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nationally defined basic basket of goods</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 13.35pt; padding-left:0.85pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Readers must currently </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">estimate this on the basis of the population and poverty rate. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We suggest that the numbers of individuals in poverty should be presented alongside poverty rates (in percentages). </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">have also previously </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">suggest</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ed</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">aid per poor person</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> is a useful and simple metric that could be included in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">annual reporting and profiles, as we have done for overall ODA in our Investments to End Poverty recipient profiles, using ODA per capita where poverty data are not available.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">DFID </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">should</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">in future:</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 29.91pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">also </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">present the numbers of individuals living in poverty to ease comparison;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 29.91pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">be clear about how national poverty measures compare with the international benchmark $1.25 a day (2005 PPP) threshold;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 29.91pt; padding-left:7.79pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">consider using ‘</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">aid per poor person</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">succinctly contextualise </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">its </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">programmes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">.</span></li></ul><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Improving poverty data</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 13.51pt; padding-left:0.69pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Investment in building statistical capacity is vital to ensure that DFID’s resources are being directed where need – extreme poverty – is greatest, and to chart progress towards ending that poverty and to ensure baselines are available for post-2015 development goals. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">It is clearly difficult to establish </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">and maintain </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">the data collection systems required to produce poverty statistics in countries affected by conflict or fragility. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">A ‘development data revolution’ required, with new technologies and approaches being considered. This presents an opportunity for DFID and the UK to lead globally.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 14.2pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">DFID’s Chief Economist suggested </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in recent evidence that countries’ </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">growth and poverty </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">trajectories </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">would be </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">core </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">elements of future </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">resource allocation decisions. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">DFID could consider including more information on future trajectories for its country programmes in future annual reports.</span></li></ol><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Other profile data &amp; regional programme profiles</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 14.2pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Some of the annual report profiles include measures of gross national income per capita. These statistics provide additional country context, particularly when presented with regional or global averages for context, as does the Sierra Leone </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and Liberia </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">profile</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> This also gives some context for the GDP growth rates included.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Some profiles also use the UN Human Development Index. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">DFID </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">c</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ould consider including GNI </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">(GDP where not available) and/</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">or Human Development Index </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">key statistics boxes for all recipient countries</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 14.2pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The regional programme profiles </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">for the sub-Saharan Africa</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Middle East and North Africa </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and Asia </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">are </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">welcome addition</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to the annual report</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> giving information on important areas of DFID spending.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">An </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">indication of average </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">regional </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">poverty levels</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">rates </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">and GNI</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">, with </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">all-developing country averages </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">would give additional context.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> Expenditures on these programmes could be added to summary table 3.1</span></li></ol><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Cross-departmental reporting</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 14.2pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">DFID </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">continues to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">provide the majority of UK ODA</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">8</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">6.6</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">% </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in 2012),</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> but ODA provided by other departments has historically been reported in less detail. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">To its credit, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">DFID has recently published new tables in the 2013 edition of DFID’s Statistics on International Development summarising UK ODA by department and breakdowns of ODA to each country by department.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> But while the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Annual Report makes </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a number of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">references to co-operation with FCO and other government departments (notably the DFID/FCO Arab Partnership), additional detail on this </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">work </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">would be welcome. </span></li></ol><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The w</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ider context: o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ther </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">development cooperation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">provi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ders and other resources</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 14.2pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Including aid received from other DAC donors would show the importance or otherwise of the UK contribution and illustrate the need for working in partnerships with others in each programme country.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 14.2pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Other providers of development cooperation from outside of the DAC are an increasingly important source of finance for developing countries</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, an estimated US$16.8 billion</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in 2011.</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> The Annual Report includes a section on emerging powers which acknowledges the growing influence of these countries internationally. It includes details on DFID’s work in building </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">development partnerships with Brazil,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> China, India and South Africa, with some specific examples. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">As the importance of non-DAC development cooperation providers grows, so DFID may wish to expand further upon its partnership work with the ’emerging powers’.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 14.2pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">There is an increasing interest, particularly in the post-2015 context, around how other resource flows, foreign investment and remittances for example, can contribute to poverty reduction. Aid and development co-operati</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">on should be viewed in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">context</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> of these wider flows.</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> The </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">profiles for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Kyrgyzstan </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and Tajikistan refer to the importance of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">remittances </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">for their economies</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, while some </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">profiles refer to investment </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">(</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">investment </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">climate</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">) and its </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">importance. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">In future, DFID’s approach to presenting other non-aid flows could be made more consistent across the profiles and expanded to include domestic capacity (for example using government spending per capita as a proxy), an </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">increasingly important consideration</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">, in future</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">.</span></li></ol><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:12pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Further information</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 14.2pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We would be pleased to help the Committee further with access to data or further information</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in support of this inquiry</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#ba0c2f; font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 17.85pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="color:#ba0c2f; font-family:Arial; font-size:7pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt"> World Bank database uses the term </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">West Bank </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">&amp; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">Gaza</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt"> DFID, </span><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/statistics-on-international-development-2013"><span style="color:#ba0c2f; font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; text-decoration:underline">Statistics on International Development 2013</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">,Oct 2013, figure 6, p23</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt"> Development Initiatives, </span><a href="http://devinit.org/report/investments-to-end-poverty/"><span style="color:#ba0c2f; font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; text-decoration:underline">Investments to End Poverty</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">, Sep 2013, pp130-131</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn4"></a><a href="#_ftnref4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt"> Sew chapter 2 of Development Initiatives, </span><a href="http://devinit.org/report/investments-to-end-poverty/"><span style="color:#ba0c2f; font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; text-decoration:underline">Investments to End Poverty</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">, Sep 2013</span></p></body></html>